(495, 1, '2015-09-02 03:33:01', '2015-09-02 03:33:01', '<h2>Sydney Cosmetic Dentist Dr Fadi Yassmin talks to Eliza Ashe of Primped about the new dental technologies that can give us a brighter, and more beautiful smile.</h2>\r\n<h1>MOUTHING OFF: A LOOK AT TEETH TRENDS</h1>\r\nBrushing and flossing your teeth is as much a part of peopleâ€™s daily routine as going to the bathroom, but having that sparkling Hollywood smile is gaining increased momentum. With Broadway Dental cosmetic dentist Dr Fadi Yassmin revealing only a quarter of people agree that they like their smile and a fifth admit they conceal their teeth in photos, itâ€™s clear that oral health is still an important issue in todayâ€™s society. We take a look at the latest developments and hero products for getting that perfect smile.\r\nOral health\r\nAustralian Dental Health Week, held in early August, highlighted a major issue with oral health is the incidence of oral cancer. Despite at least three Australians being diagnosed with oral cancer daily, it is one of the least understood conditions amongst the general public. â€œWhen we go to the dentist, we think about teeth decay and gum disease but we donâ€™t think of oral cancer. But it definitely is the most likely thing people will die of that happens in the oral category,â€ says Australian Dental Association oral health committee chairman Dr Peter Alldritt. Some of the main causes of oral cancer include tobacco and alcohol use, the sexually transmitted disease Human Papilloma Virus (HPV) and sun exposure â€“ particularly on your lips.\r\nAnother major issue for the oral health of Australians is the increasing rate of decay in childrenâ€™s teeth. A study by the University of Adelaide found between 40 and 57 per cent of 12-15 year-olds have history of decay in their permanent teeth while 48.9 per cent of six-year-old children had a history of decay in their deciduous (baby) teeth. Dr Alldritt says many of the reasons for these increasing decay rates are related to a lack of fluoride. â€œA lot of people are preferring to drink bottled water rather than tap water â€“ so theyâ€™re not getting the benefits of the fluoride in the drinking water. Decay is also being fuelled by problems in peopleâ€™s diets with high amounts of sugars and carbohydrates,â€ he says.\r\nNew technologies\r\nPrevention is key when it comes to teeth. There have been three main developments in helping dentists with the early detection of decay and thus helping prevent its occurrence, according to Dr Yassmin. These include Cariscreen which is the testing of oral bio-film (the bacteria that causes decay) which is now more readily available; the launch of the new Soprolife intra-oral diagnostic camera that helps magnify whatâ€™s in a patientâ€™s mouth; and the more common use of 3D conebeam tomography, which allows dentists to see instant radiographic imaging of vital internal structures such as sinuses, nerves, blood vessels and bones.\r\nWhile regular dental health checks are imperative to maintaining the health of your teeth, home care is also extremely important. â€œAt-home care is pivotal in oral health, brushing twice a day and flossing daily. This all aids in maintaining healthy teeth, gums and bone around the teeth preventing caries and gum disease,â€ says Dr Yassmin. Brands are constantly revolutionising the industry with new and improved oral products. Three such products include Oral-B Triumph with Smart Guide â€“ the first power toothbrush that comes with a wireless display that provides real-time feedback while you brush and the Sonicare power toothbrush by Philips that uses patented sonic technology to create a dynamic cleaning action of over 30,000 brush strokes per minute.\r\nTaking a step in the natural direction with a focus on reducing packaging landfill is Lushâ€™s Dirty Toothy Tabs which are an alternative to toothpaste and are solid tabs which you crunch to clean your teeth.\r\nWhitening\r\nCosmetically, teeth whitening remains a popular procedure. â€œTeeth whitening is still one of the most commonly asked for dental cosmetic procedures. In-chair whitening is the most common form of whitening coupled with at-home whitening kits to maintain the results,â€ reveals Dr Yassmin.\r\nIn-chair whitening sees a bleaching agent put on the teeth in a high concentration. A light or laser is then applied to the teeth to increase the temperature of the bleach to speed up the reaction. The at-home kits are trays that look a little bit like a thin mouthguard and are made up from an impression of your teeth. A bleaching gel containing a chemical similar to hydrogen peroxide is then put inside the bleaching trays and these are then worn for an hour or two every day until the desired effect is reached. â€œItâ€™s a slow and gentle procedure so the teeth donâ€™t become too sensitive as a result of whitening them,â€ says Dr Aldritt.\r\nThe biggest advance when it comes to over-the-counter items is the occurrence of toothpastes containing whitening products. â€œThey have a very low percentage of hydrogen peroxide in them, so they may potentially remove a bit of staining from your teeth and give them a whiter appearance,â€ says Dr Aldritt. Arm & Hammer is a new oral brand by Church & Dwight that has released a range of whitening products set to get your teeth glistening.\r\nWhile there have been no recent groundbreaking developments in teeth whitening, there is a product currently being refined in France that, according to the experts, will revolutionise teeth whitening. This product is set to launch in the first quarter of next year and will effect the time whitening takes, the results it delivers and the sensitivity factor, says Dr Yassmin.\r\nStraightening\r\nTraditional silver metal braces remain popular with teenagers as it is the quickest treatment and the most inexpensive, however, adults prefer alternative options. While ceramic and clear braces were popular for adults because they are less noticeable, dentists are seeing a phenomenal rise in the use of Invisalign. Invisalign uses a computer simulation to construct sequential aligners (they have the appearance of teeth whitening trays) to straighten teeth. â€œThese are very popular because you can barely tell that youâ€™re wearing them. The Invisalign technique is the most advanced and most cosmetic option out of all the orthodontic range,â€ says Dr Aldritt.\r\nPrimped â€“ Blush Hour, acting editor Eliza Ashe', 'Mouthing off: a look at teeth trends', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'mouthing-off-a-look-at-teeth-trends', '', '', '2015-09-02 08:13:53', '2015-09-02 08:13:53', '', 0, 'http://111.93.163.213/Broadwaydental/php/?post_type=article&#038;p=495', 0, 'article', '', 0),
