re best talking to your doctor who might recommend you visit a Otolaryngologist (ENT - "Ear, Nose, &amp; Throat" doctor), pulmonologist, or sleep disorders expert.\r\n\r\nI/my bed partner snore(s). Do I have apnoea?\r\n\r\nThat could be the case but not necessarily.\r\n\r\nSome people who do not have OSA snore. Most importantly, pay attention to the sound and pattern of snoring - if it is a loud, frequent snoring that occurs in periodic bursts punctuated by periods of silence, normal breathing, and/or gasping for air, you are probably looking at OSA.', 'Sleep Apnoea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-14 00:42:32', '2015-09-14 00:42:32', '', 240, 'http://111.93.163.213/Broadwaydental/php/240-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
