(1034, 1, '2015-09-14 04:54:36', '2015-09-14 04:54:36', '<iframe style="padding-bottom: 20px;" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/gheJfAQRgcA?rel=0&amp;showinfo=0&amp;controls=1&amp;autohide=1" width="390" height="219" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe>\r\n<div class="inn_contant">\r\n<h3>FAQ''S ABOUT SLEEP APNOEA</h3>\r\n<h4>GETTING A GOOD NIGHT''S SLEEP</h4>\r\n<h4>OBSTRUCTIVE SLEEP APNOEA - FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</h4>\r\n<h4>How severe must sleep apnoea be to require treatment?</h4>\r\n<h4>For any type of apnoea to be considered of importance it must be at least 10 seconds in duration or longer. Specialists usually consider 5 or more of such apnoeas per hour to be of possible clinical significance (less than 5 per hour is normal).</h4>\r\nHow do I know if I have it?\r\nOne of the best people to help you answer this question is your bed partner. People with sleep apnoea generally have the following symptoms:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Loud, frequent snoring,</li>\r\n	<li>Poor daytime concentration,</li>\r\n	<li>Irritability and mood changes</li>\r\n	<li>Daytime sleepiness, fatigue and tiredness,</li>\r\n	<li>Impotence and reduced sex drive,</li>\r\n	<li>Need to frequently go to the toilet at night,</li>\r\n	<li>Episodes of gasping, snorting or choking during sleep,</li>\r\n	<li>Lack of energy and endurance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf I were awakening in the night and having all these symptoms, wouldn''t I be aware of it?\r\n\r\nProbably not. Most people with Sleep Apnoea are unaware that they wake up to breathe many times during the night. Many become accustomed to these brief interruptions but they are significant enough to disrupt the sleep pattern. That''s why they feel sleepy when they are awake. A majority of Sleep Apnoea sufferers go through most of their lives without knowing they suffer this condition.\r\n\r\nWhat should I do if I think I may have sleep apnoea?\r\n\r\nIf you suspect you could be suffering from Sleep Apnoea, you are best talking to your doctor who might recommend you visit a Otolaryngologist (ENT - "Ear, Nose, &amp; Throat" doctor), pulmonologist, or sleep disorders expert.\r\n\r\nI/my bed partner snore(s). Do I have apnoea?\r\n\r\nThat could be the case but not necessarily.\r\n\r\nSome people who do not have OSA snore. Most importantly, pay attention to the sound and pattern of snoring - if it is a loud, frequent snoring that occurs in periodic bursts punctuated by periods of silence, normal breathing, and/or gasping for air, you are probably looking at OSA.\r\n</div>', 'Sleep Apnoea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-14 04:54:36', '2015-09-14 04:54:36', '', 240, 'http://111.93.163.213/Broadwaydental/php/240-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
