essure (CPAP)\r\n\r\nA device that pumps air under pressure into the airway, keeping the windpipe open during sleep. Unfortunately, a significant number of people with sleep apnoea find the mask difficult to tolerate.\r\n\r\n\r\nMandibular Advancement Splints (Mouthguards)\r\n\r\n\r\nMandibular repositioning appliances reposition and maintain the lower jaw in a forward position during sleep. This opens the upper airway and repositions the lower jaw and tongue in a more forward position away from the throat.\r\n\r\nDental Splints are comfortable and easy to wear and most people find that it only takes a couple of weeks to become acclimatised to wearing them.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Sleep Apnoea Treatment Process', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1111-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-15 01:58:52', '2015-09-15 01:58:52', '', 1111, 'http://111.93.163.213/Broadwaydental/php/1111-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1149, 1, '2015-09-15 02:26:21', '2015-09-15 02:26:21', '<div class="inn_contant">\n<h3>BED TIME TIPS</h3>\n\n<h3>GETTING A GOOD NIGHT''S SLEEP</h3>\n\n<h3>OBSTRUCTIVE SLEEP APNOEA - BEDTIME TIPS</h3>\n\n\n\n<h4>Tired of being elbowed by your partner every night?</h4>\n\nPut an end to your snoring sessions today - whether you do it for them or whether you do it for you, the important thing is to do it now!\n\nGet your physician to study your sleep patterns and seek appropriate treatment if you are diagnosed with Obstructive Sleep Disorder.\n\nHowever, before you talk to Dr Yassmin about potentially having a Dental Splint fitted to your mouth to treat Sleep Apnoea, there are a few things you can do to minimise your snoring:\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Raise your head up while sleeping. Elevate your body from the waist up by using a foam wedge or the head of your bed by four to six inches. Cervical pillows are also recommended.</li>\n	<li>Sleep on your side. Avoid sleeping on your back, as your tongue and soft tissues are more likely to drop and obstruct your airway. To keep yourself from rolling onto your back while you sleep, some suggest sewing a tennis ball into a pocket on the back of your pyjama top. Others go as far as recommending wedging a pillow stuffed with tennis balls behind your back.</li>\n	<li>Open your nasal passages. Try using a saline spray, nasal dilator or breathing strips regularly.</li>\n	<li>Throat exercises to reduce sleep apnoea. Throat exercises may reduce the severity of Sleep Apnoea by strengthening the muscles in the airway, making them less likely to collapse. Here are some exercises you can practice regularly:</li>\n\n<li>Press your tongue on the roof of your mouth and hold it there three minutes a day.</li>\n\n<li> Press your tongue flat against the floor of your mouth and brush sides and top with a toothbrush. Repeat brushing movement five times, three times a day.</li>\n\n<li>Purse your lips in a kiss-like movement. Hold your lips tightly together and move them up and to the right, then up and to the left 10 times. Repeat this exercise three times.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>', 'Bed Time Tips', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '250-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-09-15 02:26:21', '2015-09-15 02:26:21', '', 250, 'http://111.93.163.213/Broadwaydental/php/250-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
